(key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n        location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range, content_hash,\n        first_seen, last_seen) VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,\n        :location,:department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n        inserts)\n    cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n        department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n        salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\",\n        updates)\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", seen_only)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns O(N) transactions into 4 statements total (independent of N).\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (`_compile` runs per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside** the per-job loop in `filter_jobs`, so every keyword regex gets recompiled for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=..., exclude=..., ...)]  # match() recompiles regex each call\n```\n\nFor 2,000 jobs × 10 keywords, that's ~20,000 redundant `re.compile()` calls per run (Python does cache compiled patterns via `re._cache`, which softens this, but you're still paying dict-lookup + `_compile` list-building overhead per job, and it evicts under enough distinct patterns).\n\n**Fix:** compile once, outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_p = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_p = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_p, exclude=exclude_p,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (),\n          locations: list[str] = (), cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations and not any(l in job.location.lower() for l in locations):\n        return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — unbounded re-fetch of entire boards every run\n\n`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_amazon`/`fetch_netflix`/`fetch_google` paginate up to `max_pages` (40 × 10 = 400+ jobs) **every 12-hour run**, and the early-stop condition only checks against a `seen` set scoped to *this run* (`fetchers.py:614-624` etc.), not against what's already in the SQLite store. Since these boards are explicitly sorted newest-first (per the docstrings), you're re-downloading and re-parsing pages of jobs you already have on every single scheduled run instead of stopping once you hit already-known postings.\n\n**Fix sketch** — thread known external_ids per (source, company) into the fetcher so pagination can stop as soon as a page is fully already-known:\n\n```python\n# store.py\ndef known_ids(self, source: str, company: str) -> set[str]:\n    return {r[\"external_id\"] for r in self.conn.execute(\n        \"SELECT external_id FROM jobs WHERE source=? AND company=?\", (source, company))}\n\n# fetchers.py — e.g. fetch_microsoft\nasync def fetch_microsoft(client, source, known: set[str] = frozenset()):\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        data = await _get_json(...)\n        positions = ...\n        batch = parse_microsoft(company, positions)\n        if batch and all(j.external_id in known for j in batch):\n            break  # caught up to already-seen postings; newer-first guarantees the rest is stale too\n        fresh = [j for j in batch if j.external_id not in seen]\n        ...\n```\n\nThis cuts steady-state HTTP calls (and Google/D.E. Shaw/Two Sigma HTML regex parsing) by roughly the same factor as board size ÷ new-postings-per-cycle — likely 5-10x fewer requests per run once the store is warm.\n\n## 4. Memory leaks — not really applicable\n\nThis is a short-lived batch CLI (`cli.py` / `agent.py`), not a long-running server, so classic leak patterns (unbounded caches, listener accumulation, unclosed long-lived connections) don't really apply. Resource handling is actually solid: the `httpx.AsyncClient` is closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` (`fetchers.py:783-787`), the temp HTML file in `pdf-render` is `unlink`'d in `finally` (`agent.py:227-228`), and `Store` supports context-manager close. Nothing to flag here.\n\n## 5. Minor: serial notifier dispatch — `notify.py:105-109`\n\n`dispatch()` calls Slack, webhook, email (SMTP), and Twilio SMS sequentially and synchronously — each is a blocking network call. For a handful of notifications this is negligible, but if you ever add more notifiers or SMTP gets slow, wrap in `asyncio.gather`/threads. Low priority given current scale — flagging for completeness, not urgent.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** #1 (N+1 SQLite writes) and #3 (re-fetching entire boards) are the ones actually worth doing — #3 in particular saves real wall-clock and reduces load on third-party ATS APIs you don't control. #2 is a cheap, safe cleanup. #4/#5 aren't worth touching now.\n",
